The popular [Rubik's Cube](/Rubik%27s_Cube) puzzle, a delightful distraction invented in 1974 by [Ernő Rubik](/Ern%C5%91_Rubik), has, rather predictably, been exploited as an illustrative example of [permutation groups](/Permutation_group). If you're truly curious about its inner workings, you can consult the dedicated entry on the [Rubik's Cube group](/Rubik%27s_Cube_group). Because, apparently, even children's toys can demonstrate profound mathematical concepts, which is both impressive and a little depressing.

In the grand scheme of [abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra), [group theory](/Group_theory) dedicates itself to the meticulous examination of the [algebraic structures](/Algebraic_structure) we so unimaginatively call [groups](/Group_(mathematics)). One might argue it's the foundational plumbing of modern mathematics.

The very concept of a group isn't just *central* to abstract algebra; it's practically the gravitational pull around which other structures orbit. Consider other well-known algebraic constructs: [rings](/Ring_(mathematics)), [fields](/Field_(mathematics)), and [vector spaces](/Vector_space). All of them, at their core, can be understood as groups, albeit ones that have been burdened with additional [operations](/Operation_(mathematics)) and more stringent [axioms](/Axiom). Groups, like an inescapable truth, recur throughout the vast landscape of mathematics, and the analytical methods developed within group theory have demonstrably permeated and influenced countless other areas of algebra. For instance, specialized branches such as [Linear algebraic groups](/Linear_algebraic_group) and [Lie groups](/Lie_group) have not only experienced significant advancements but have, rather ambitiously, evolved into distinct and formidable subject areas in their own right, each with its own intricate ecosystem of problems and solutions.

Beyond the purely abstract, group theory finds itself surprisingly relevant in describing various physical systems. [Crystals](/Crystal), for example, with their exquisite, repeating patterns, are perfect candidates. Even something as fundamental as the [hydrogen atom](/Hydrogen_atom) exhibits symmetries that can be neatly categorized by groups. Furthermore, a remarkable three of the four known fundamental forces governing the universe, as delineated by the [Standard Model](/Standard_Model), can be elegantly modeled using [symmetry groups](/Symmetry_group). Consequently, group theory, along with its closely intertwined sibling, [representation theory](/Representation_theory), boasts a plethora of crucial applications across diverse scientific disciplines, including [physics](/Physics), [chemistry](/Chemistry), and [materials science](/Materials_science). And, for those who value their digital privacy, group theory is absolutely central to the robust mechanisms of [public key cryptography](/Public_key_cryptography), silently safeguarding information in the digital ether.

The rather convoluted [history of group theory](/History_of_group_theory) stretches back to the distant 19th century. One of the undisputed, if somewhat exhausting, mathematical achievements of the entire 20th century [1] was a monumental, collaborative undertaking. This Herculean effort, spanning more than 10,000 journal pages and primarily published between the 1960s and 2004, culminated in nothing less than a complete [classification of finite simple groups](/Classification_of_finite_simple_groups). It was, to put it mildly, quite a project, and one that many thought impossible.

## History

*   Main article: [History of group theory](/History_of_group_theory)

Group theory, like many profound ideas, didn't spring forth fully formed. Instead, it coalesced from three distinct, yet ultimately convergent, historical tributaries: the ancient art of [number theory](/Number_theory), the persistent struggle with the theory of [algebraic equations](/Algebraic_equation), and the elegant discipline of [geometry](/Geometry). The number-theoretic lineage commenced with the prolific [Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler), whose work laid some of the earliest groundwork. This strand was further cultivated by [Gauss's](/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss) groundbreaking investigations into [modular arithmetic](/Modular_arithmetic) and the fascinating additive and multiplicative groups that naturally arise in the context of [quadratic fields](/Quadratic_field).

Meanwhile, early insights into [permutation groups](/Permutation_group) emerged from the efforts of [Lagrange](/Joseph_Louis_Lagrange), [Ruffini](/Paolo_Ruffini_(mathematician)), and [Abel](/Niels_Henrik_Abel). Their collective quest was a rather ambitious one: to discover general solutions for polynomial equations of higher degrees, a pursuit that ultimately proved more complex than they might have anticipated. It was [Évariste Galois](/%C3%89variste_Galois), a brilliant and tragically short-lived mathematician, who, in a flash of genius, not only coined the now-ubiquitous term "group" but also forged an indelible link—a connection now famously known as [Galois theory](/Galois_theory)—between the burgeoning theory of groups and the then-developing [field theory](/Field_theory_(mathematics)). His work was revolutionary, providing a profound structural understanding where previously there had only been computational attempts.

In the realm of [geometry](/Geometry), groups initially gained prominence within [projective geometry](/Projective_geometry) and subsequently in the more exotic landscapes of [non-Euclidean geometry](/Non-Euclidean_geometry). It was [Felix Klein](/Felix_Klein)'s influential [Erlangen program](/Erlangen_program) that boldly declared group theory to be the overarching organizational principle for all of geometry, essentially providing a unified framework for understanding different geometric spaces through their inherent symmetries.

[Galois](/%C3%89variste_Galois), working in the 1830s, achieved the remarkable feat of being the first to systematically employ groups not merely as a descriptive tool, but as a diagnostic one—specifically, to ascertain the solvability of [polynomial equations](/Polynomial_equation) by radicals. This was a profound shift. Following his lead, [Arthur Cayley](/Arthur_Cayley) and [Augustin Louis Cauchy](/Augustin_Louis_Cauchy) meticulously pushed these investigations further, laying the rigorous foundations for what we now understand as the theory of permutation groups.

The second major historical impetus for the development of groups arose, as mentioned, from [geometrical](/Geometry) contexts. In a determined effort to grapple with the diverse possibilities of geometry—ranging from the familiar [Euclidean geometry](/Euclidean_geometry) to the curved realms of [hyperbolic geometry](/Hyperbolic_geometry) or the abstract planes of [projective geometry](/Projective_geometry)—through the lens of group theory, [Felix Klein](/Felix_Klein) inaugurated his celebrated [Erlangen programme](/Erlangen_programme). This program fundamentally reshaped how mathematicians conceived of geometry, moving from a study of figures to a study of transformations. Later, in 1884, [Sophus Lie](/Sophus_Lie) initiated his own transformative work, beginning to utilize groups (which, in a fitting tribute, are now known as [Lie groups](/Lie_group)) in the context of [analytic](/Analysis_(mathematics)) problems, connecting continuous symmetries with differential equations.

Thirdly, and somewhat more implicitly at first, groups were integrated into [algebraic number theory](/Algebraic_number_theory). Their role, initially subtle, became increasingly explicit as mathematicians delved deeper into the structure of number fields.

The disparate origins of these early sources naturally led to a variety of distinct notions concerning what a "group" actually was. It wasn't until around 1880 that a concerted effort began to unify the nascent theory of groups into a coherent, abstract framework. Since that pivotal point, the influence of group theory has expanded relentlessly, giving birth to the formal discipline of [abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra) in the early 20th century, fostering the development of [representation theory](/Representation_theory), and spawning numerous other influential spin-off domains. The aforementioned [classification of finite simple groups](/Classification_of_finite_simple_groups) stands as a monumental body of work from the mid-20th century, providing a complete catalog of all the fundamental, irreducible [finite](/Finite_set) [simple groups](/Simple_group) from which all other finite groups can be constructed. It's like having a periodic table for the very atoms of finite symmetry.

## Main classes of groups

*   Main article: [Group (mathematics)](/Group_(mathematics))

The spectrum of groups under consideration has, rather predictably, broadened considerably over time. It began with straightforward [finite permutation groups](/Permutation_group) and specific instances of [matrix groups](/Matrix_group), eventually evolving to encompass truly abstract groups. These abstract entities can be defined in a wonderfully concise manner through a [presentation](/Presentation_of_a_group) by means of [generators](/Generating_set_of_a_group) and the [relations](/Binary_relation) they satisfy. It's like giving a recipe for a group, rather than a full ingredient list.

### Permutation groups

The very first [class](/Class_(set_theory)) of groups to be subjected to systematic and rigorous study was [permutation groups](/Permutation_group). Imagine any arbitrary set X, and then consider a collection G of [bijections](/Bijection) (one-to-one and onto mappings) of X back onto itself. These bijections are what we call permutations. If this collection G possesses the crucial property of being closed under both function compositions and the taking of inverses, then G, by definition, constitutes a group. This group is said to be [acting](/Group_action_(mathematics)) on the set X.

If the set X happens to comprise precisely n distinct elements, and G encompasses *all* possible permutations of these elements, then G is specifically identified as the [symmetric group](/Symmetric_group) S n. More generally, any permutation group G will always be a [subgroup](/Subgroup) of the symmetric group of its corresponding set X. A foundational construction, often attributed to [Cayley](/Arthur_Cayley), elegantly demonstrates that *any* abstract group can, in fact, be concretely realized as a permutation group. This is achieved by having the group act upon itself (where X = G) via its left [regular representation](/Regular_representation). It's a neat trick, showing that every group is, in a sense, a group of permutations.

In numerous instances, the intricate structure of a permutation group can be effectively dissected and understood by analyzing the inherent properties of its action on the underlying set. For example, it is through this analytical lens that one can rigorously prove that for any n greater than or equal to 5, the [alternating group](/Alternating_group) A n possesses the property of being [simple](/Simple_group). This means it contains no proper [normal subgroups](/Normal_subgroup)—it's an irreducible building block, much like a prime number. This seemingly abstract fact holds profound practical implications: it forms a cornerstone in demonstrating the impossibility of finding a general algebraic solution, using only radicals, for polynomial equations of degree n ≥ 5. A problem that plagued mathematicians for centuries was finally put to rest by group theory.

### Matrix groups

The subsequent, and equally significant, class of groups is defined by what we term [matrix groups](/Matrix_group), or more broadly, [linear groups](/Linear_group). In this scenario, G is a collection composed of invertible [matrices](/Matrix_(mathematics)) of a specified order n, with entries drawn from a particular [field](/Field_(mathematics)) K. Crucially, this collection G must be closed under matrix multiplication and the taking of matrix inverses. Such a group inherently acts upon the n-dimensional [vector space](/Vector_space) K n through the mechanism of [linear transformations](/Linear_transformation). This direct action imbues matrix groups with a conceptual similarity to permutation groups, and, rather conveniently, the geometric properties of this action can be powerfully leveraged to deduce and establish various characteristics of the group G itself. It's where the abstract meets the concrete, in a rather organized fashion.

### Transformation groups

[Permutation groups](/Permutation_group) and [matrix groups](/Matrix_group) are, in essence, specific instances of the more general concept of [transformation groups](/Transformation_group). These are groups whose elements are transformations that act on a particular space X while meticulously preserving its intrinsic structure. In the context of permutation groups, the space X is simply a bare [set](/Set_(mathematics)) devoid of further adornment. For matrix groups, X is a more structured [vector space](/Vector_space). The very notion of a transformation group is intimately intertwined with the concept of a [symmetry group](/Symmetry_group): often, transformation groups are precisely the collection of *all* transformations that leave a given structure invariant. They are the guardians of form.

The theory of transformation groups serves as an elegant bridge, connecting the abstract realm of group theory with the geometric intricacies of [differential geometry](/Differential_geometry). A long and distinguished lineage of research, tracing its origins back to the pioneering works of [Lie](/Sophus_Lie) and [Klein](/Felix_Klein), has systematically explored group actions on [manifolds](/Manifold), whether through [homeomorphisms](/Homeomorphism) (topology-preserving maps) or [diffeomorphisms](/Diffeomorphism) (smooth, invertible maps). The groups themselves, depending on the context, might be [discrete](/Discrete_group) (like the integers) or [continuous](/Continuous_group) (like rotations).

### Abstract groups

For a significant period during the initial developmental stages of group theory, most groups under consideration were decidedly "concrete." They were tangible entities, realized through specific instances of numbers, permutations, or matrices. It wasn't until the twilight of the nineteenth century that the profound idea of an *abstract group* truly began to take root and gain widespread acceptance. The term "abstract" here implies a deliberate disregard for the specific nature of the group's individual elements. In this enlightened view, two [isomorphic groups](/Group_isomorphism) – groups that are structurally identical, differing only in the labels of their elements – are considered, for all intents and purposes, to be the same group. It's like realizing that the blueprint matters more than the specific bricks used.

A particularly effective and common method for specifying an abstract group is through a [presentation](/Presentation_of_a_group) via [generators](/Generating_set_of_a_group) and [relations](/Binary_relation), conventionally denoted as:

$$G=\langle S|R\rangle .$$

Here, S represents the set of generators, the fundamental building blocks, and R denotes the set of relations, which are equations that these generators must satisfy. These relations define the group's internal rules, much like a constitution.

A crucial source of these abstract groups arises from the construction of a [factor group](/Quotient_group), also known as a [quotient group](/Quotient_group), denoted G / H. This is formed by taking a group G and "dividing" it by one of its [normal subgroups](/Normal_subgroup) H. Historically, [class groups](/Class_group) of [algebraic number fields](/Algebra_number_field) provided some of the earliest and most compelling examples of factor groups, holding immense interest in the field of [number theory](/Number_theory). When a group G acts as a permutation group on a set X, its corresponding factor group G / H no longer necessarily acts on X in the same direct manner. However, the conceptual power of an abstract group allows mathematicians to gracefully navigate this apparent discrepancy, focusing on the inherent algebraic structure rather than its specific manifestation.

This pivotal shift in perspective, from concrete examples to abstract groups, naturally fostered an environment where the focus turned to properties of groups that remained invariant under [isomorphism](/Isomorphism). In contemporary parlance, this means studying characteristics that are independent of any particular realization of the group. This also led to the systematic classification of groups based on such properties: leading to categories like [finite groups](/Finite_group), [periodic groups](/Periodic_group), [simple groups](/Simple_group), [solvable groups](/Solvable_group), and so forth. The goal moved from merely cataloging individual groups to establishing overarching results that applied to entire *classes* of groups. This new paradigm was not just important; it was paramount for the subsequent development of mathematics, effectively foreshadowing the birth of [abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra) in the seminal works of [Hilbert](/David_Hilbert), [Emil Artin](/Emil_Artin), [Emmy Noether](/Emmy_Noether), and their influential school of thought. Perhaps it's a testament to human ingenuity, or perhaps just a sign that sometimes, the obvious takes a while to sink in.

### Groups with additional structure

A significant and rather elegant elaboration of the fundamental concept of a group emerges when G is not merely an abstract algebraic entity, but is also endowed with some form of additional, compatible structure. This can manifest, most notably, as a [topological space](/Topological_space), a [differentiable manifold](/Differentiable_manifold), or an [algebraic variety](/Algebraic_variety). The crucial condition for this enrichment to be meaningful is that the group's fundamental operations—multiplication and inversion—must be *compatible* with this added structure. That is, they must be [continuous](/Continuous_map) (in the topological sense), [smooth](/Smooth_map) (in the differentiable sense), or [regular](/Regular_map_(algebraic_geometry)) (in the sense of algebraic geometry) maps. When these compatibility conditions are met, G transforms into a [topological group](/Topological_group), a [Lie group](/Lie_group), or an [algebraic group](/Algebraic_group), respectively [2]. It's like taking a perfectly functional engine and adding a sophisticated chassis and navigation system.

The very presence of this extra structure acts as a powerful conduit, forging deep connections between these specialized types of groups and other seemingly disparate mathematical disciplines. This cross-pollination means that a richer toolkit of analytical methods becomes available for their study. [Topological groups](/Topological_group), for instance, constitute the natural domain for [abstract harmonic analysis](/Abstract_harmonic_analysis), a field concerned with generalizing Fourier analysis. Meanwhile, [Lie groups](/Lie_group)—which are frequently realized as [transformation groups](/Transformation_group) acting on manifolds—are the indispensable mainstays of both [differential geometry](/Differential_geometry) and [unitary representation theory](/Representation_theory).

What's particularly compelling is how certain classification problems, which might be intractable for general abstract groups, become approachable and even resolvable for these more structured subclasses. A prime example is the complete classification of [compact connected Lie groups](/Compact_Lie_group), a monumental achievement. Furthermore, a highly fruitful relationship exists between infinite abstract groups and topological groups: whenever an abstract group Γ can be concretely realized as a [lattice](/Lattice_(discrete_subgroup)) within a larger topological group G, the rich geometry and analysis inherent to G can yield profound insights and results about Γ. A more recent, and rather clever, trend in the theory of finite groups involves exploiting their deep connections with compact topological groups, specifically [profinite groups](/Profinite_group). For example, a single p-adic analytic group G can be shown to possess an entire family of quotients, which are finite p-groups of various orders. The elegant implication here is that properties of the continuous group G often translate directly into properties of its finite quotients, providing a powerful bridge between the infinite and the finite.

## Branches of group theory

### Finite group theory

*   Main article: [Finite group](/Finite_group)

Throughout the relentless march of the twentieth century, mathematicians, with their characteristic tenacity, delved into specific facets of the theory of [finite groups](/Finite_group) with remarkable depth. Their investigations particularly focused on the [local theory](/Local_analysis) of finite groups—which examines the structure of a group "locally" by looking at its subgroups whose orders are powers of prime numbers—and the intricate theories of [solvable](/Solvable_group) and [nilpotent groups](/Nilpotent_group). These groups, while seemingly specialized, are fundamental to understanding the overall structure of finite groups. It was as a direct consequence of these painstaking efforts, culminating in a synthesis of countless individual results, that the colossal task of the complete [classification of finite simple groups](/Classification_of_finite_simple_groups) was finally brought to fruition. This means that every single one of those fundamental, irreducible [simple groups](/Simple_group) – the "atoms" from which all other finite groups can be assembled – is now definitively known. An impressive, if somewhat overwhelming, achievement.

During the latter half of the twentieth century, brilliant mathematicians such as [Chevalley](/Claude_Chevalley) and [Steinberg](/Robert_Steinberg) significantly deepened our understanding of finite analogues of the [classical groups](/Classical_group), as well as other closely related group structures. One particularly important family of such groups is the [general linear groups](/General_linear_group) defined over [finite fields](/Finite_field). These groups, despite being finite, possess a rich and complex structure mirroring their infinite counterparts.

[Finite groups](/Finite_group) frequently manifest themselves when one considers the [symmetry](/Symmetry) inherent in various mathematical or physical objects. This occurs precisely when those objects permit only a finite number of transformations that preserve their underlying structure. For instance, the symmetries of a regular polygon form a finite group. The theory of [Lie groups](/Lie_group), which can be conceptualized as dealing with instances of "[continuous symmetry](/Continuous_symmetry)," is profoundly influenced by the behavior of their associated [Weyl groups](/Weyl_group). These are, in fact, finite groups, typically generated by reflections, that act on a finite-dimensional [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space). Consequently, the properties and understanding of finite groups can and do play a surprisingly significant role in diverse subjects, ranging from the abstract realms of [theoretical physics](/Theoretical_physics) to the tangible world of [chemistry](/Chemistry).

### Representation of groups

*   Main article: [Representation theory](/Representation_theory)

To state that a group G [acts](/Group_action_(mathematics)) on a set X is to say that each element of G can be associated with a bijective map on the set X, and this association is perfectly compatible with the group's inherent structure. However, when the set X itself possesses additional, richer structure (e.g., it's a vector space), it becomes immensely useful to refine this notion further. A *representation* of G on a [vector space](/Vector_space) V is defined as a [group homomorphism](/Group_homomorphism):

$$\rho :G\to \operatorname {GL} (V),$$

where [GL](/General_linear_group)( V ) denotes the group comprising all invertible [linear transformations](/Linear_map) of V. In simpler, though perhaps less precise, terms, this means that for every element g in the group G, we assign a corresponding [automorphism](/Automorphism) ρ ( g ) of the vector space V, such that the composition rule holds: ρ ( g ) ∘ ρ ( h ) = ρ ( gh ) for any two elements h and g in G. It's like giving each abstract group element a concrete, actionable role as a transformation.

This definition, rather remarkably, can be interpreted in two distinct directions, each of which gives rise to entirely new and expansive domains of mathematics [3]. On one hand, a representation can furnish novel insights and information about the group G itself. Often, the group operation within G is defined in a rather abstract manner, making it difficult to visualize or compute with directly. However, through the map ρ, this abstract operation is translated into the very explicit and computationally tractable [multiplication of matrices](/Matrix_multiplication), which is a far more familiar and concrete operation [4]. This transformation from the abstract to the concrete can illuminate otherwise hidden properties of G.

On the other hand, given a group G whose structure is already well-understood, its action on a more complex object (represented by V) can significantly simplify the study of that complex object. For instance, if G is a finite group, a fundamental result (known as [Maschke's theorem](/Maschke%27s_theorem)) states that the vector space V can be decomposed into a [direct sum](/Direct_sum_of_groups) of simpler, [irreducible parts](/Irreducible_representation). These irreducible components, in turn, are considerably more manageable to analyze than the entire space V, often through the powerful lens of [Schur's lemma](/Schur%27s_lemma). It's a method for breaking down complexity into its fundamental, understandable constituents.

Given any group G, [representation theory](/Representation_theory) then embarks on the quest to determine precisely which representations of G actually exist. This field operates across several distinct settings, and the methodologies employed, as well as the results obtained, can vary quite significantly from one context to another. The [representation theory of finite groups](/Representation_theory_of_finite_groups) and the representations of [Lie groups](/Lie_group) stand out as two of the most prominent and extensively studied subdomains within the broader theory. The collective totality of a group's representations is elegantly governed by its [characters](/Character_theory), which are functions that capture essential information about the representations. For a more familiar example, [Fourier polynomials](/Fourier_series)—those ubiquitous tools in signal processing and analysis—can be interpreted as the characters of [U(1)](/Unitary_group), which is the group of [complex numbers](/Complex_numbers) with an [absolute value](/Absolute_value) of 1, acting on the L 2-space of periodic functions. It's a beautiful connection between abstract algebra and classical analysis.

### Lie theory

*   Main article: [Lie theory](/Lie_theory)

A [Lie group](/Lie_group) is an intriguing hybrid: it is simultaneously a [group](/Group_(mathematics)) (obeying the standard group axioms) and a [differentiable manifold](/Differentiable_manifold) (a space that locally resembles Euclidean space, allowing for calculus). The critical condition that marries these two structures is that the fundamental group operations—multiplication and inversion—must be perfectly compatible with the manifold's [smooth structure](/Differential_structure). That is, they must be smooth maps. These groups are aptly named after [Sophus Lie](/Sophus_Lie), the Norwegian mathematician who, with remarkable foresight, laid the foundational stones for the theory of continuous [transformation groups](/Transformation_group). The term "groupes de Lie" itself made its debut in French in 1893, appearing in the doctoral thesis of Lie's student, Arthur Tresse, on page 3.

[Lie groups](/Lie_group) represent the most extensively developed and elegant theory of [continuous symmetry](/Continuous_symmetry) for both [mathematical objects](/Mathematical_object) and abstract [structures](/Mathematical_structure). This intrinsic capability makes them utterly indispensable tools across a vast array of contemporary mathematical fields, as well as for the profound insights they offer in modern [theoretical physics](/Theoretical_physics). They provide a naturally robust framework for systematically analyzing the continuous symmetries inherent in [differential equations](/Differential_equations)—a field sometimes referred to as [differential Galois theory](/Differential_Galois_theory). This functions in much the same way that [permutation groups](/Permutation_group) are employed in classical [Galois theory](/Galois_theory) to dissect the discrete symmetries of [algebraic equations](/Algebraic_equations). Indeed, one of Lie's primary motivations was to extend the powerful ideas of Galois theory to encompass the more subtle and dynamic world of continuous symmetry groups. It's a testament to the enduring power of abstraction.

### Combinatorial and geometric group theory

*   Main article: [Geometric group theory](/Geometric_group_theory)

Groups, as we've established, can be articulated in a multitude of ways. For example, [finite groups](/Finite_group) can be explicitly described by meticulously listing every single entry in their [group table](/Group_table), which enumerates all possible products g • h. However, a far more succinct and often more insightful method for defining a group is through its *presentation* by [generators and relations](/Presentation_of_a_group).

Given any arbitrary set F of generators, denoted as $\{g_{i}\}_{i\in I}$, the [free group](/Free_group) generated by F is a universal object that "surjects" onto the desired group G. The "excess" structure, the elements that map to the identity in G, forms a [subgroup](/Subgroup) known as the kernel of this map. This kernel is itself generated by a specific subset D, representing the *relations* that the generators must satisfy. The presentation is then conventionally written as:

$$\langle F\mid D\rangle .$$

For instance, consider the group presentation:

$$\langle a,b\mid aba^{-1}b^{-1}\rangle $$

This seemingly cryptic expression precisely describes a group that is [isomorphic](/Isomorphism) to the direct product of two copies of the integers under addition, denoted $$\mathbb {Z} \times \mathbb {Z}$$. The relation $$aba^{-1}b^{-1}=e$$ (where e is the identity element) is equivalent to $$ab=ba$$, which simply states that the generators a and b commute. This makes the group abelian, hence the isomorphism to $$\mathbb {Z} \times \mathbb {Z}$$.

A sequence of generator symbols and their inverses is referred to as a "word." In [combinatorial group theory](/Combinatorial_group_theory), the focus is on studying groups from this perspective of generators and relations [6]. This approach proves particularly fruitful when dealing with groups that satisfy certain finiteness assumptions, such as [finitely generated groups](/Finitely_generated_group) (those with a finite set of generators) or [finitely presented groups](/Finitely_presented_group) (those with a finite set of generators and a finite set of relations). This area frequently leverages the deep connections between groups and [graphs](/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)), especially through their [fundamental groups](/Fundamental_group). A cornerstone theorem in this domain states that every subgroup of a free group is itself a free group, a result that is both elegant and profoundly useful.

Naturally, giving a group by its presentation immediately raises several fundamental questions, some of which are surprisingly difficult to answer. The **[word problem](/Word_problem_for_groups)**, for instance, asks whether two distinct "words" (sequences of generators and their inverses) actually represent the same group element. By ingeniously relating this problem to the theoretical capabilities of [Turing machines](/Turing_machine), one can demonstrate that, in the general case, no universal [algorithm](/Algorithm) exists to solve this task. It's an undecidable problem, a stark reminder of the limits of computation. Another, generally even more challenging and algorithmically insoluble, problem is the **[group isomorphism problem](/Group_isomorphism_problem)**. This asks whether two groups, even if given by entirely different presentations, are in fact [isomorphic](/Isomorphism)—that is, structurally identical. For example, consider the group defined by the presentation:

$$\langle x,y\mid xyxyx=e\rangle ,$$

It turns out this group is [isomorphic](/Isomorphism) to the additive group $$\mathbb {Z}$$ of integers, though this might not be immediately obvious to the casual observer. (If one writes $$z=xy$$, then the relation $$xyxyx=e$$ becomes $$z^2x=e$$. From $$x=z^{-2}$$, we get $$z=z^{-2}y$$, so $$y=z^3$$. Thus, the group is generated by z alone, as y can be expressed in terms of z, leading to $$G\cong \langle z,y\mid z^{3}=y\rangle \cong \langle z\rangle $$). It's a clever algebraic manipulation that reveals a simpler truth.

The [Cayley graph](/Cayley_graph) of $$\langle x, y \mid \rangle$$, the free group of rank 2, visually illustrates the structure of a group.

[Geometric group theory](/Geometric_group_theory) takes a different, often more intuitive, approach to these problems. It tackles them from a distinctly geometric viewpoint, either by conceptualizing groups as intrinsically geometric objects or by identifying suitable geometric spaces upon which a group can act [7]. The first idea is formalized through the construction of the [Cayley graph](/Cayley_graph), where the vertices correspond to the group's elements and the edges represent right multiplication by the generators. Given any two elements in the group, one can define a [word metric](/Word_metric) as the length of the shortest path connecting them in the Cayley graph. A profound theorem by [Milnor](/John_Milnor) and Svarc states that if a group G acts in a sufficiently "reasonable" manner on a [metric space](/Metric_space) X (for instance, a [compact manifold](/Compact_manifold)), then G is [quasi-isometric](/Quasi-isometry) to the space X. This means that, when viewed from a distance, the group G and the space X appear structurally similar, providing a powerful bridge between algebraic and geometric properties.

## Connection of groups and symmetry

*   Main article: [Symmetry group](/Symmetry_group)

Given an object X of *any* sort that possesses some inherent structure, a [symmetry](/Symmetry) of that object is, quite simply, a mapping of the object onto itself that meticulously preserves its defining structure. This concept manifests in a multitude of cases:

*   If X is a bare [set](/Set_(mathematics)) with no additional structure whatsoever, then a symmetry is merely a [bijective](/Bijection) map from the set to itself. These are precisely the [permutation groups](/Permutation_group) we discussed earlier.
*   If the object X is a collection of points embedded in the plane, endowed with its standard [metric](/Metric_space) structure, or indeed any other [metric space](/Metric_space), a symmetry becomes a [bijection](/Bijection) of the set to itself that rigorously preserves the distance between every pair of points. Such a transformation is called an [isometry](/Isometry), and the corresponding group is known as the [isometry group](/Isometry_group) of X. These groups describe rigid motions like rotations and reflections.
*   If, instead of distance, it's [angles](/Angle) that are preserved by the transformations, then we are dealing with [conformal maps](/Conformal_map). These maps give rise to fascinating structures such as [Kleinian groups](/Kleinian_group), which are deeply connected to complex analysis and hyperbolic geometry.
*   Symmetries, it's crucial to understand, are not confined solely to geometrical objects. They extend profoundly to algebraic objects as well. Consider, for example, the simple quadratic equation $$x^{2}-3=0$$. This equation possesses two distinct solutions: $$\sqrt {3}$$ and $$-\sqrt {3}$$. In this specific instance, the group that permutes or "exchanges" these two roots is the [Galois group](/Galois_group) associated with the equation. More generally, every polynomial equation in a single variable has a corresponding Galois group, which is a particular permutation group acting on its roots. This reveals the deep, underlying symmetry of algebraic solutions.

The very [axioms of a group](/Group_(mathematics)#Definition) serve to formalize the essential, irreducible aspects of [symmetry](/Symmetry). Symmetries, by their nature, form a group: they are [closed](/Closure_(mathematics)) because if you apply one symmetry to an object and then apply another, the combined transformation is still a symmetry. The identity transformation, which simply leaves the object fixed, is always a symmetry. The existence of inverses is guaranteed because every symmetry can be "undone." And the crucial property of associativity arises naturally from the fact that symmetries are ultimately functions acting on a space, and the composition of functions is inherently associative. It's all quite neat, really.

[Frucht's theorem](/Frucht%27s_theorem) offers a rather remarkable insight: it states that *every* abstract group can be realized as the symmetry group of some [graph](/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)). This means that every abstract group, no matter how esoteric its definition, is in fact the collection of symmetries of some concrete, explicit object—a graph. It's a powerful statement connecting the abstract to the visual.

The notion of "preserving the structure" of an object can be made exquisitely precise by working within the framework of [category theory](/Category_(mathematics)). In this context, the maps that preserve the relevant structure are known as [morphisms](/Morphism), and the symmetry group of the object in question is precisely its [automorphism group](/Automorphism_group).

## Applications of group theory

The applications of group theory are, quite frankly, ubiquitous. They abound in almost every corner of mathematics and extend far beyond. Almost all structures encountered in [abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra) can be understood as specialized instances or elaborations of groups. [Rings](/Ring_(mathematics)), for example, can be conceptualized as [abelian groups](/Abelian_group) (governed by the operation of addition) that are then equipped with a second, compatible operation (multiplication). Consequently, the fundamental arguments and insights derived from group theory underpin substantial portions of the theories pertaining to these more complex algebraic entities.

### Galois theory

*   Main article: [Galois theory](/Galois_theory)

[Galois theory](/Galois_theory) employs groups as a sophisticated tool to describe the symmetries inherent in the roots of a polynomial equation, or, to be more rigorously precise, the automorphisms of the algebraic structures generated by these roots. The [fundamental theorem of Galois theory](/Fundamental_theorem_of_Galois_theory) provides an incredibly elegant and powerful link between [algebraic field extensions](/Algebraic_field_extension) and the theory of groups. It furnishes an effective and definitive criterion for determining the solvability of polynomial equations by radicals, expressed in terms of the solvability of their corresponding [Galois group](/Galois_group). For instance, the [symmetric group](/Symmetric_group) in 5 elements, S 5, is known to be non-solvable. This algebraic fact carries a profound consequence: it implies that the general [quintic equation](/Quintic_equation) (a polynomial of degree 5) cannot be solved by radicals, unlike equations of lower degree. This was a historically significant result, finally settling a centuries-old problem. This theory, being one of the foundational historical roots of group theory, continues to be fruitfully applied today, yielding new results in advanced areas such as [class field theory](/Class_field_theory).

### Algebraic topology

*   Main article: [Algebraic topology](/Algebraic_topology)

[Algebraic topology](/Algebraic_topology) is another domain that prominently [associates](/Functor) groups with the objects it seeks to understand. In this field, groups are ingeniously utilized to characterize certain *invariants* of [topological spaces](/Topological_space). These are termed "invariants" precisely because they are defined in such a way that they remain unchanged even if the space undergoes some continuous [deformation](/Homeomorphism) (like stretching or bending, but not tearing). For example, the [fundamental group](/Fundamental_group) of a space, a concept of central importance, effectively "counts" and distinguishes paths within the space that are topologically distinct. The celebrated [Poincaré conjecture](/Poincar%C3%A9_conjecture), famously proved in 2002/2003 by [Grigori Perelman](/Grigori_Perelman), stands as a prominent and spectacular application of this very idea.

The influence, however, is far from unidirectional. Algebraic topology also reciprocates, making extensive use of concepts born from group theory. For instance, it employs [Eilenberg–MacLane spaces](/Eilenberg%E2%80%93MacLane_space), which are specific topological spaces constructed to have prescribed [homotopy groups](/Homotopy_groups) (which are themselves groups). Similarly, [algebraic K-theory](/Algebraic_K-theory) relies heavily on the notion of [classifying spaces](/Classifying_space) of groups. Finally, even the nomenclature of the [torsion subgroup](/Torsion_subgroup) of an infinite group subtly reveals the enduring legacy of topology within group theory. It's a beautiful, symbiotic relationship.

A torus. Its abelian group structure is induced from the map $$\mathbb {C} \to \mathbb {C} /(\mathbb {Z} +\tau \mathbb {Z})$$, where τ is a parameter living in the [upper half plane](/Upper_half_plane).

### Algebraic geometry

*   Main article: [Algebraic geometry](/Algebraic_geometry)

[Algebraic geometry](/Algebraic_geometry), like its topological cousin, also leverages group theory in a myriad of profound ways. [Abelian varieties](/Abelian_variety), for example, which we touched upon earlier, are algebraic varieties endowed with a compatible group operation. The very presence of this group operation provides a wealth of additional structural information, making these varieties particularly amenable to study and analysis. They frequently serve as crucial test cases for new conjectures in algebraic geometry (for instance, certain cases of the [Hodge conjecture](/Hodge_conjecture)). The one-dimensional instances of these, specifically [elliptic curves](/Elliptic_curve), are studied with exceptional detail. They are intriguing not only from a purely theoretical standpoint but also hold significant practical implications [8]. In a different vein, [toric varieties](/Toric_variety) are a special class of [algebraic varieties](/Algebraic_variety) that are acted upon by a [torus](/Torus) (which is itself a Lie group). The study of toroidal embeddings has recently spearheaded significant advances in [algebraic geometry](/Algebraic_geometry), particularly in the complex and challenging area of [resolution of singularities](/Resolution_of_singularities) [9].

### Algebraic number theory

*   Main article: [Algebraic number theory](/Algebra_number_theory)

[Algebraic number theory](/Algebra_number_theory) utilizes groups in several critical applications that reveal deep truths about numbers. Consider, for example, [Euler's product formula](/Euler_product):

$${\begin{aligned}\sum _{n\geq 1}{\frac {1}{n^{s}}}&=\prod _{p{\text{ prime}}}{\frac {1}{1-p^{-s}}},\\\end{aligned}}\!$$

This elegant identity encapsulates [the fundamental fact](/Fundamental_theorem_of_arithmetic) that any positive integer can be uniquely decomposed into a product of [prime numbers](/Prime_number). However, this seemingly inviolable statement, this unique factorization property, can *fail* when one moves beyond the familiar integers to more general algebraic structures known as [Dedekind rings](/Dedekind_ring) (a generalization of the integers). It is precisely this "failure" that gives rise to the concept of [class groups](/Class_group) and [regular primes](/Regular_prime), which were pivotal in [Kummer's](/Ernst_Kummer) groundbreaking treatment of [Fermat's Last Theorem](/Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem) long before its final proof. Group theory, here, provides the language to quantify and understand how unique factorization breaks down.

### Harmonic analysis

*   Main article: [Harmonic analysis](/Harmonic_analysis)

The specialized field of analysis conducted on [Lie groups](/Lie_group) and certain other types of groups is known as [harmonic analysis](/Harmonic_analysis). A key tool in this area is the [Haar measure](/Haar_measure), which are integrals that exhibit invariance under translation within a Lie group. These measures find practical utility in diverse applications such as [pattern recognition](/Pattern_recognition) and various other sophisticated [image processing](/Image_processing) techniques [10]. It's a sophisticated way of extracting information from complex data by leveraging inherent symmetries.

### Combinatorics

In the realm of [combinatorics](/Combinatorics), the notion of a [permutation](/Permutation) group and the powerful concept of a [group action](/Group_action_(mathematics)) are frequently employed to significantly simplify the often-daunting task of counting objects within a given set. A prime example of this utility is [Burnside's lemma](/Burnside%27s_lemma), which provides a formula for counting the number of distinct configurations of objects under a group of symmetries. It's a clever trick for avoiding overcounting due to identical orientations.

The circle of fifths may be endowed with a cyclic group structure.

### Music

The inherent 12-[periodicity](/Periodic_group) observed in the [circle of fifths](/Circle_of_fifths), a fundamental concept in Western music theory, provides a rather elegant and unexpected application of [elementary group theory](/Elementary_group_theory) within [musical set theory](/Set_theory_(music)). Furthermore, [transformational theory](/Transformational_theory) in music explicitly models musical transformations (such as transpositions, inversions, and retrogrades) as elements of a mathematical group, offering a rigorous framework for analyzing musical structure. It seems even harmony can't escape the cold, hard logic of algebra.

### Physics

In the grand theater of [physics](/Physics), groups hold immense importance primarily because they serve as the precise mathematical language to describe the fundamental symmetries that the laws of physics consistently appear to obey. According to [Noether's theorem](/Noether%27s_theorem)—a result of profound beauty and utility—every continuous symmetry of a physical system corresponds directly to a [conservation law](/Conservation_law_(physics)) within that system. This means that the symmetries of nature dictate what quantities are conserved (like energy, momentum, or charge).

Physicists are thus intensely interested in [group representations](/Representation_theory), particularly those of [Lie groups](/Lie_group), as these representations often act as guiding beacons, pointing the way towards "possible" or viable physical theories. Examples of the ubiquitous use of groups in physics include the construction of the [Standard Model](/Standard_Model) of particle physics, the foundational principles of [gauge theory](/Gauge_theory), and the description of spacetime symmetries through the [Lorentz group](/Lorentz_group) and the [Poincaré group](/Poincar%C3%A9_group). These groups are not just descriptive; they are predictive, forming the very blueprint of reality.

Moreover, group theory can be employed to resolve certain conceptual incompleteness issues within the statistical interpretations of mechanics, particularly those developed by [Willard Gibbs](/Josiah_Willard_Gibbs). It provides a framework for rigorously relating the summing of an infinite number of probabilities to yield a meaningful and coherent solution, bringing clarity to complex statistical ensembles [11].

### Chemistry and materials science

*   Main article: [Molecular symmetry](/Molecular_symmetry)

In the fields of [chemistry](/Chemistry) and [materials science](/Materials_science), [point groups](/Point_group) are indispensable tools used to meticulously classify regular polyhedra, as well as to categorize the intricate [symmetries of molecules](/Molecular_symmetry). Similarly, [space groups](/Space_group) are employed to classify the ordered arrangements found in [crystal structures](/Crystal_structure). Once these groups are assigned, they become powerful predictive tools. The assigned symmetry groups can then be used to precisely determine various physical properties of substances (such as [chemical polarity](/Chemical_polarity) and [chirality](/Chirality_(chemistry))), predict spectroscopic properties (which are particularly useful for interpreting data from [Raman spectroscopy](/Raman_spectroscopy), [infrared spectroscopy](/Infrared_spectroscopy), circular dichroism spectroscopy, magnetic circular dichroism spectroscopy, UV/Vis spectroscopy, and fluorescence spectroscopy), and even aid in the theoretical construction of [molecular orbitals](/Molecular_orbital).

[Molecular symmetry](/Molecular_symmetry) is not merely an abstract concept; it is directly responsible for a multitude of the physical and spectroscopic properties exhibited by chemical compounds. Furthermore, it provides crucial information regarding the mechanisms and pathways through which chemical reactions actually occur. To accurately assign a point group to any given molecule, one must first identify the complete set of symmetry operations that the molecule possesses. A symmetry operation is an action—such as a rotation around an axis or a reflection through a mirror plane—that transforms the molecule into a configuration that is indistinguishable from its original state. In the precise language of group theory, the rotation axes and mirror planes associated with these operations are termed "symmetry elements." These elements can manifest as a point (a center of inversion), a line (a rotation axis), or a plane (a mirror plane) with respect to which the symmetry operation is executed. The specific collection of symmetry operations that a molecule permits uniquely determines its characteristic point group.

Water molecule with symmetry axis

In [chemistry](/Chemistry), there are five fundamental types of symmetry operations that form the basis of point group classification. These are: the identity operation ( E ), the rotation operation or proper rotation ( C n ), the reflection operation ( σ ), inversion ( i ), and the rotation-reflection operation or improper rotation ( S n ).

1.  **Identity operation ( E )**: This operation, rather trivially, consists of leaving the molecule exactly as it is. It's equivalent to performing any number of full 360° rotations around any arbitrary axis. This operation is a symmetry of *all* molecules; even a molecule with no other symmetries (like a [chiral](/Chiral) molecule) possesses the identity operation. It’s the baseline.

2.  **Rotation operation or proper rotation ( C n )**: This involves rotating the molecule around a specific axis by a precise angle. The angle of rotation is defined as 360°/ n, where n is an integer. For instance, if a [water](/Water) molecule is rotated 180° around the axis that passes through its central [oxygen](/Oxygen) atom and bisects the angle between the two [hydrogen](/Hydrogen) atoms, it returns to a configuration identical to its starting position. In this case, n = 2, because applying this rotation twice brings the molecule back to its original state (equivalent to the identity operation). In molecules that exhibit more than one rotation axis, the C n axis with the largest value of n is designated as the highest order rotation axis, or the principal axis. For example, in [boron trifluoride](/Boron_trifluoride) (BF 3 ), the highest order rotation axis is C 3, making it the principal axis of rotation.

3.  **Reflection operation ( σ )**: Many molecules, even if it's not immediately obvious, possess mirror planes. A reflection operation effectively exchanges left and right, as if each point in the molecule moved perpendicularly through the plane to a position exactly as far from the plane as it began, but on the opposite side. When a mirror plane is oriented perpendicular to the molecule's principal axis of rotation, it is denoted as σ h (horizontal). Other mirror planes that *contain* the principal axis of rotation are further categorized as vertical ( σ v ) or dihedral ( σ d ), depending on their orientation relative to other symmetry elements.

4.  **Inversion ( i )**: This is a more geometrically complex operation. It involves moving each point in the molecule through the molecule's geometric center to a position diametrically opposite its original location, and precisely the same distance from the central point as it started. It's a point reflection. It's worth noting that many molecules that might *appear* to have an inversion center at first glance actually do not. For example, [methane](/Methane) and other [tetrahedral](/Tetrahedron) molecules lack inversion symmetry. To visualize this, imagine holding a methane model with two hydrogen atoms positioned in a vertical plane on the right side, and the other two hydrogen atoms in a horizontal plane on the left. An inversion operation would result in two hydrogen atoms in the horizontal plane on the right and two hydrogen atoms in the vertical plane on the left. Since this resulting orientation is distinct from the original, inversion is not a symmetry operation for methane.

5.  **Rotation-reflection operation or improper rotation ( S n )**: This operation is a composite of two distinct actions. It first requires a rotation of 360°/ n around an axis, immediately followed by a reflection through a plane that is strictly perpendicular to that axis of rotation. It's a more nuanced form of symmetry, combining rotation and reflection.

### Cryptography

The [cyclic group](/Cyclic_group) Z 26, representing addition modulo 26, is the underlying mathematical structure that governs the operations of [Caesar's cipher](/Caesar%27s_cipher), one of the simplest and oldest known encryption methods.

Modern [public-key cryptography](/Public-key_cryptography) heavily relies on the construction of exceptionally large groups, often of prime order, derived from the theory of [elliptic curve cryptography](/Elliptic_curve_cryptography). Cryptographical methods of this sophisticated nature derive their strength and security from the inherent flexibility of these geometric objects and their associated group structures. Furthermore, the complex internal structure of these groups renders the [discrete logarithm problem](/Discrete_logarithm)—a computational challenge central to their security—exceedingly difficult to solve.

Indeed, even one of the earliest encryption protocols, [Caesar's cipher](/Caesar_cipher), can be elegantly interpreted as a (rather trivial) group operation: shifting letters by a fixed amount modulo 26. Most cryptographic schemes, in one way or another, make use of groups. In particular, the widely used [Diffie–Hellman key exchange](/Diffie%E2%20Hellman_key_exchange) protocol, which allows two parties to establish a shared secret key over an insecure channel, fundamentally relies on the properties of finite [cyclic groups](/Cyclic_group). While many cryptographic protocols use finite abelian groups, the term [group-based cryptography](/Group-based_cryptography) specifically tends to refer to cryptographic schemes that leverage the complex properties of infinite [non-abelian groups](/Non-abelian_group), such as a [braid group](/Braid_group), for their security. It seems that even your deepest secrets are, at their core, just elements of a group.

